begin model
##################
# Model metadata #
##################
#---
# Model title: Structure-based mechanistic model for MEK and ERK activation by mutant BRAF (V600E)
# Contributors:
# - NIH/NCI Research Project CA244660 team 
# - MPIs: Hlavacek WS, Kholodenko BN, Lemmon MA, Radhakrishnan R (alphabetical order)
# Summary:
# - A goal of building this model is to identify gaps in our mechanistic understanding.
# - This model is intended to serve as a stepping stone toward a model that captures the effects
#   of combinations of conformation-selective RAF- and MEK-specific kinase inhibitors.
#---
#---
# Cell type considered in the model:
# - HeLa Kyoto cells
# Comments:
# - Absolute protein copy numbers have been reported for this cell line (Hein et al., 2015).
#---
#---
# Compartments considered in the model:
# - cytosol (cyt)
# - nucleus (nuc)
#---
#---
# References:
# - Catalanotti F et al. (2009) Nat Struct Mol Biol 16:294-303. 
# - Fischmann TO et al. (2009) Biochemistry 48:2661-2674.
# - Haling JR et al. (2014) Cancer Cell 26:402-413.
# - Hein MY, ..., Mann M (2015) Cell 163:712-723.
# - Kocieniewski P, Lipniacki T (2013) Phys Biol 10:035006.
# - Lee N, Lee JW, Kang GY, Park SH, Kim KP (2019) Proteomics 19:1900086.
# - Ohren JF et al. (2004) Nat Struct Mol Biol 11:1192-1197
# - Piala AT, Humphreys JM, Goldsmith EJ (2014) Biophys J 107:2006-2015.
# - Resing KA, ..., Ahn NG (1995) Biochemistry 34:2610-2620.
# - Stagni C et al. (2018) Mol Cancer Ther 17:1332-1340.
# - Yuan J et al. (2018) Sci Signal 11:eaar6795.
# - Zlotek‐Zlotkiewicz E, ..., Pie. M (2015) J Cell Biol 211:765-774.
#---
begin parameters
#---
# fraction of a cell to consider in a stochastic simulation
# comments:
# - The scaling factor f should multiply volumes, copy numbers 
#   and rate constants for zero-order processes 
#   (e.g., a synthesis reaction having a constant rate).
# - This parameter can be set to a value <1 to accelerate stochastic simulation.
# - The value of f has no effect on the speed of a deterministic (ODE-based) simulation.
f 1 # dimensionless, 0<f<=1
#---
#---
# Avogadro constant
NA 6.02214076e23 # number of molecules/particles per mole (exact value)
#---
#---
# compartment volumes
# comments:
# - Hein et al. (2015) use a total cell volume of 2 pL to convert estimates
#   of absolute protein copy numbers per cell to cellular concentrations.
#   See Table S3 (an Excel spreadsheet included in the supplemental material).
# - Cell volume varies during the cell cycle without significant changes 
#   in dry mass (Zlotek‐Zlotkiewicz et al., 2015).
#   Zlotek‐Zlotkiewicz et al. (2015) measured a total cell volume of 1.67 pL for
#   newborn HeLa cells and 3.53 pL for pre-mitotic HeLa cells. See Figure S2, panel C.
Vtot 2e-12*f # L per cell
Vrat 4 # dimensionless (rough estimate of total volume:nuclear volume ratio)
Vnuc=Vtot/Vrat # L per cell 
Vcyt=Vtot-Vnuc # L per cell 
#---
#---
# total protein abundances in HeLa Kyoto cells 
# See Table S3 in Hein et al. (2015).
ARAF_cpc     32680*f # copies per cell,     27.13 nM
BRAF_cpc     19164*f # copies per cell,     15.91 nM
CRAF_cpc      2067*f # copies per cell,      1.72 nM
KSR1_cpc      1692*f # copies per cell,      1.41 nM
KSR2_cpc         0*f # copies per cell       0.00 nM (not detected)
MEK1_cpc    261981*f # copies per cell,    217.52 nM
MEK2_cpc    396724*f # copies per cell,    329.39 nM
ERK1_cpc     67298*f # copies per cell,     55.88 nM
ERK2_cpc    300375*f # copies per cell,    249.39 nM
YWHAE_cpc 16080848*f # copies per cell, 13,351.44 nM
YWHAZ_cpc  6408998*f # copies per cell,  5,321.20 nM
#---
#---
# typical rate constant for protein-protein association
kf_typical 1e6/(NA*Vcyt) # /M/s converted to /(molecule/cell)/s
#---
#---
# parameters for inactive MEK1 binding to BRAF 
# See Figure 2B in Haling et al. (2014).
kf_MEK1_BRAF 8.219e5/(NA*Vcyt) # /M/s converted to /(molecule/cell)/s
kr_MEK1_BRAF 3.523e-2 # /s  
KD_MEK1_BRAF=kr_MEK1_BRAF/kf_MEK1_BRAF # 43 nM
#---
#---
# parameters for homodimerization of inactive MEK1 
# See Figure 2B in Yuan et al. (2018).
KD_MEK1_MEK1 1.5e-6*(NA*Vcyt) # M converted to molecule/cell
kf_MEK1_MEK1=kf_typical # /(molecule/cell)/s
kr_MEK1_MEK1=kf_MEK1_MEK1*KD_MEK1_MEK1 # /s
#---
#---
# parameters for heterodimerization of inactive MEK1 and inactive MEK2 
# See Figure 4A in Catalanotti et al. (2009).
KD_MEK1_MEK2=0.92*KD_MEK1_MEK1 # molecule/cell
kf_MEK1_MEK2=kf_typical # /(molecule/cell)/s
kr_MEK1_MEK2=kf_MEK1_MEK2*KD_MEK1_MEK2 # /s
#---
#---
# parameters for homodimerization of inactive MEK2
# See Figure 4A in Catalanotti et al. (2009).
# KD_MEK2_MEK2>>KD_MEK1_MEK1 is consistent with Supplementary Tables 1 and 2 in Ohren et al. (2004).
KD_MEK2_MEK2=310*KD_MEK1_MEK1 # molecule/cell
kf_MEK2_MEK2=kf_typical # /(molecule/cell)s/
kr_MEK2_MEK2=kf_MEK2_MEK2*KD_MEK2_MEK2 # /s
#---

#######################################################################################

KD_BRAFV600E_BRAFV600E 10e-9 # M
kf_BRAFV600E_BRAFV600E=kf_typical/(NA*Vcyt) # /(molecule/cell)/s
kr_BRAFV600E_BRAFV600E=kf_typical*KD_BRAFV600E_BRAFV600E # /s

kf_MEK2_BRAF=kf_MEK1_BRAF
kr_MEK2_BRAF=kr_MEK1_BRAF

# parameters for RAF-mediated phosphorylation of MEK
Ceff_RAF_MEK 1e-5 # M
KM_RAF_MEK 1e-6 # M
kcat_RAF_MEK 1 # /s
keff_BRAFV600E_MEK1_S218=Ceff_RAF_MEK*kcat_RAF_MEK/KM_RAF_MEK
keff_BRAFV600E_MEK1_S222=Ceff_RAF_MEK*kcat_RAF_MEK/KM_RAF_MEK
keff_BRAFV600E_MEK2_S222=Ceff_RAF_MEK*kcat_RAF_MEK/KM_RAF_MEK
keff_BRAFV600E_MEK2_S226=Ceff_RAF_MEK*kcat_RAF_MEK/KM_RAF_MEK
# parameters for MEK-mediated phosphorylation of ERK
Ceff_MEK_ERK 1e-5 # M
KM_MEK_ERK 1e-6 # M
kcat_MEK_ERK 1 # /s
keff_MEK1_ERK1_T202=Ceff_MEK_ERK*kcat_MEK_ERK/KM_MEK_ERK
keff_MEK1_ERK1_Y204=Ceff_MEK_ERK*kcat_MEK_ERK/KM_MEK_ERK
keff_MEK2_ERK1_T202=Ceff_MEK_ERK*kcat_MEK_ERK/KM_MEK_ERK
keff_MEK2_ERK1_Y204=Ceff_MEK_ERK*kcat_MEK_ERK/KM_MEK_ERK
keff_MEK1_ERK2_T185=Ceff_MEK_ERK*kcat_MEK_ERK/KM_MEK_ERK
keff_MEK1_ERK2_Y187=Ceff_MEK_ERK*kcat_MEK_ERK/KM_MEK_ERK
keff_MEK2_ERK2_T185=Ceff_MEK_ERK*kcat_MEK_ERK/KM_MEK_ERK
keff_MEK2_ERK2_Y187=Ceff_MEK_ERK*kcat_MEK_ERK/KM_MEK_ERK
Ceff_ERK_MEK=Ceff_MEK_ERK
KM_ERK_MEK 1e-6 # M
kcat_ERK_MEK 1 # /s
keff_ERK1_MEK1_T292=Ceff_ERK_MEK*kcat_ERK_MEK/KM_ERK_MEK
keff_ERK2_MEK1_T292=Ceff_ERK_MEK*kcat_ERK_MEK/KM_ERK_MEK
# parameters for reversible MEK-ERK association
kf_MEK1_ERK1 1e6/(NA*Vcyt) # /(molecule/cell)/s
kr_MEK1_ERK1 0.1 # /s
kf_MEK1_ERK2 1e6/(NA*Vcyt) # /(molecule/cell)/s
kr_MEK1_ERK2 0.1 # /s
kf_MEK2_ERK1 1e6/(NA*Vcyt) # /(molecule/cell)/s
kr_MEK2_ERK1 0.1 # /s
kf_MEK2_ERK2 1e6/(NA*Vcyt) # /(molecule/cell)/s
kr_MEK2_ERK2 0.1 # /s
# steric factor
phi 0.3 # dimensionless
# rate constant for constitutive dephosphorylation of phosphosites
kpase 2 # /s
end parameters
begin molecule types
#list of small-molecule drugs of interest: 
# - vemurafenib
# - sorafenib
# - tremetinib
# - cobimetinib
#YWHAE() # 14-3-3 epsilon
#YWHAZ() # 14-3-3 zeta 
#ARAF(RBD,CRD,S214~0~P)
#BRAF(RBD,CRD,S365~0~P,S729~0~P)
#CRAF(RBD,CRD,S259~0~P) 
#KSR1()
#KSR2()
BRAFV600E(DIF,aG) 
# BRAF
# - DIF: dimerization interface mediating RAF-RAF and RAF-KSR interactions
#        A prominent structural feature of the DIF is the aC-b4 loop.
#        RAF forms back-to-back anti-parallel dimers.
# - aG: interface responsible for RAF-MEK interactions
#       A prominent structural feature of this interface is the aG helix in the C-lobe of the kinase.
#       MEK forms face-to-face dimers with MEK, RAF, and KSR.
MEK1(D,S218~0~P,S222~0~P,T292~0~P,aG) 
# MAP2K1
# - D: D motif
#      The D motif is recognized by the DRS in ERK.
# - S218/S222: sites of phosphorylation in the activation loop (aka T-loop)
# - T292: negative feedback site phosphorylated by ERK 
#         This site putatively serves to recruit phosphatase.
#         T292 is located within a proline-rich insert of the kinase domain sequence.
# - aG: interace responsible for MEK-RAF interactions
#       A prominent feature of this interface is the aG helix in the C-lobe of the kinase.
#       MEK forms face-to-face dimers with MEK, RAF, and KSR.
MEK2(D,S222~0~P,S226~0~P,aG) 
# MAP2K2
# - D: D motif
# - S222/S226: sites of phosphorylation in the activation loop (aka T-loop)
# - NB: the T292 site in MEK1 is missing in MEK2.
# - aG: interace responsible for MEK-RAF interactions
ERK2(T185~0~P,Y187~0~P,DRS) 
# MAPK1
# - T185/Y187: TxY motif (TEY in ERK, TGY in p38, TPY in JNK)
# - DRS: D recognition site (binds MEK and substrates with D motifs)
# - FRS: F recognition site (binds substrates with F motifs)
ERK1(T202~0~P,Y204~0~P,DRS)
# MAPK3
# - T202/Y204: TxY motif
# - DRS: D recognition site (binds MEK and substrates with D motifs)
# - FRS: F recognition site (only competent for binding to an F motif when the TxY motif is doubly phosphorylated)
end molecule types
begin seed species
# For simplicity, we assume that the V600E mutation is homozygous.
# BRAF copy number and mutant allele percentage are heterogeneous 
# in tumors of patients with metastatic melanoma (Stagni et al., 2018).
BRAFV600E(DIF,aG) BRAF_cpc 
MEK1(D,S218~0,S222~0,T292~0,aG) MEK1_cpc
MEK2(D,S222~0,S226~0,aG) MEK2_cpc
ERK2(T185~0,Y187~0,DRS) ERK2_cpc
ERK1(T202~0,Y204~0,DRS) ERK1_cpc
end seed species
begin observables
Molecules BRAF_monomers BRAFV600E(DIF,aG)
Species BRAF_dimers BRAFV600E(DIF!1).BRAFV600E(DIF!1)
Molecules MEK1_BRAF_interfaces MEK1(aG!1).BRAFV600E(aG!1)
Molecules MEK2_BRAF_interfaces MEK2(aG!1).BRAFV600E(aG!1)
Species MEK1x2_BRAFx2_tetramers MEK1(aG!1).BRAFV600E(DIF!2,aG!1).BRAFV600E(DIF!2,aG!3).MEK1(aG!3)
Species MEK1_MEK2_BRAFx2_tetramers MEK1(aG!1).BRAFV600E(DIF!2,aG!1).BRAFV600E(DIF!2,aG!3).MEK2(aG!3)
Species MEK2x2_BRAFx2_tetramers MEK2(aG!1).BRAFV600E(DIF!2,aG!1).BRAFV600E(DIF!2,aG!3).MEK2(aG!3)
Species MEK1_homodimers MEK1(aG!1).MEK1(aG!1)
Molecules MEK1_MEK2_heterodimers MEK1(aG!1).MEK2(aG!1)
Species MEK2_homodimers MEK2(aG!1).MEK2(aG!1)
Molecules ppMEK1 MEK1(S218~P,S222~P)
Molecules ppMEK2 MEK2(S222~P,S226~P)
Molecules ppERK1 ERK1(T202~P,Y204~P)
Molecules ppERK2 ERK2(T185~P,Y187~P)
Molecules pT292_MEK1 MEK1(T292~P!?)
end observables
begin functions
end functions
begin reaction rules
###############################
# reversible RAF dimerization #
###############################
# reversible dimerization of mutant BRAF(V600E)
BRAFV600E(DIF)+BRAFV600E(DIF)<->BRAFV600E(DIF!1).BRAFV600E(DIF!1) kf_BRAFV600E_BRAFV600E,kr_BRAFV600E_BRAFV600E
################################## 
# reversible MEK-RAF association #
##################################
# Does binding depend on phosphorylation state of MEK? <<---- Q1 (Yes)
# Can MEK bind RAF and ERK at the same time? <<---- Q2 (Yes? No?) Here, the rules are formulated such that the answer to the Q is "no."
# reversible MEK1/2 binding to monomeric and dimeric forms of mutant BRAF
# We assume that MEK activation-loop phosphorylation inhibits MEK-RAF binding.
BRAFV600E(aG)+MEK1(D,S218~0,S222~0,aG)<->BRAFV600E(aG!1).MEK1(D,S218~0,S222~0,aG!1) kf_MEK1_BRAF,kr_MEK1_BRAF
BRAFV600E(aG)+MEK1(D,S218~P,S222~0,aG)<->BRAFV600E(aG!1).MEK1(D,S218~P,S222~0,aG!1) phi*kf_MEK1_BRAF,(1/phi)*kr_MEK1_BRAF
BRAFV600E(aG)+MEK1(D,S218~0,S222~P,aG)<->BRAFV600E(aG!1).MEK1(D,S218~0,S222~P,aG!1) phi*kf_MEK1_BRAF,(1/phi)*kr_MEK1_BRAF
BRAFV600E(aG)+MEK1(D,S218~P,S222~P,aG)<->BRAFV600E(aG!1).MEK1(D,S218~P,S222~P,aG!1) phi^2*kf_MEK1_BRAF,(1/phi^2)*kr_MEK1_BRAF
BRAFV600E(aG)+MEK2(D,S222~0,S226~0,aG)<->BRAFV600E(aG!1).MEK2(D,S222~0,S226~0,aG!1) kf_MEK2_BRAF,kr_MEK2_BRAF
BRAFV600E(aG)+MEK2(D,S222~P,S226~0,aG)<->BRAFV600E(aG!1).MEK2(D,S222~P,S226~0,aG!1) phi*kf_MEK2_BRAF,(1/phi)*kr_MEK2_BRAF
BRAFV600E(aG)+MEK2(D,S222~0,S226~P,aG)<->BRAFV600E(aG!1).MEK2(D,S222~0,S226~P,aG!1) phi*kf_MEK2_BRAF,(1/phi)*kr_MEK2_BRAF 
BRAFV600E(aG)+MEK2(D,S222~P,S226~P,aG)<->BRAFV600E(aG!1).MEK2(D,S222~P,S226~P,aG!1) phi^2*kf_MEK2_BRAF,(1/phi^2)*kr_MEK2_BRAF 
################################################## 
# RAF-mediated activating phosphorylation of MEK #
##################################################
# We assume a non-processive mechanism.
# We assume proximity-mediated catalysis.
# We assume that phosphorylation is ordered. See Resing et al. (1995).
# We assume that pS222 in MEK1 (pS226 in MEK2) is required for phosphorylation of S218 in MEK1 (S222 in MEK2).
BRAFV600E(aG!1).MEK1(S218~0,S222~P,aG!1)->BRAFV600E(aG!1).MEK1(S218~P,S222~P,aG!1) keff_BRAFV600E_MEK1_S218
BRAFV600E(aG!1).MEK1(S222~0,aG!1)->BRAFV600E(aG!1).MEK1(S222~P,aG!1) keff_BRAFV600E_MEK1_S222
BRAFV600E(aG!1).MEK2(S222~0,S226~P,aG!1)->BRAFV600E(aG!1).MEK2(S222~P,S226~P,aG!1) keff_BRAFV600E_MEK2_S222
BRAFV600E(aG!1).MEK2(S226~0,aG!1)->BRAFV600E(aG!1).MEK2(S226~P,aG!1) keff_BRAFV600E_MEK2_S226
###############################
# reversible MEK dimerization #
###############################
# Can MEK bind ERK and RAF at the same time? <<---- Q2
# Inactive MEK does not dimerize (Fischmann et al., 2009). <<---- Is this correct?
# We assume that only fully activated MEK is capable of dimerization.
MEK1(D,S218~P,S222~P,aG)+MEK1(D,S218~P,S222~P,aG)<->MEK1(D,S218~P,S222~P,aG!1).MEK1(D,S218~P,S222~P,aG!1) kf_MEK1_MEK1,kr_MEK1_MEK1
MEK1(D,S218~P,S222~P,aG)+MEK2(D,S222~P,S226~P,aG)<->MEK1(D,S218~P,S222~P,aG!1).MEK2(D,S222~P,S226~P,aG!1) kf_MEK1_MEK2,kr_MEK1_MEK2
MEK2(D,S222~P,S226~P,aG)+MEK2(D,S222~P,S226~P,aG)<->MEK2(D,S222~P,S226~P,aG!1).MEK2(D,S222~P,S226~P,aG!1) kf_MEK2_MEK2,kr_MEK2_MEK2
###########################
# MEK autophosphorylation #
###########################
# Does MEK autophosphorylation happen? Is MEK a substrate of MEK? <<---- Q3
################################## 
# reversible MEK-ERK association #
##################################
# What about competition between MEK and cytosolic ERK substrates for ERK binding? <<---- Q4
# MEK-ERK binding is independent of phosphorylation states of MEK and ERK?? <<---- Q5
# Has the MEK-ERK interface been characterized? <<----Q6
# Is there cooperativity in binding of MEK dimers to ERK dimers? <<---- Q7
# There seems to be the possiblity of two-point attachment:
# the two D motifs in a MEK dimer can simultaneously bind the two DRS motifs in an ERK dimer.
MEK1(D,aG)+ERK1(DRS)<->MEK1(D!1,aG).ERK1(DRS!1) kf_MEK1_ERK1,kr_MEK1_ERK1
MEK1(D,aG)+ERK2(DRS)<->MEK1(D!1,aG).ERK2(DRS!1) kf_MEK1_ERK2,kr_MEK1_ERK2
MEK2(D,aG)+ERK1(DRS)<->MEK2(D!1,aG).ERK1(DRS!1) kf_MEK2_ERK1,kr_MEK2_ERK1
MEK2(D,aG)+ERK2(DRS)<->MEK2(D!1,aG).ERK2(DRS!1) kf_MEK2_ERK2,kr_MEK2_ERK2
###################################################################
# MEK-mediated activating phosphorylation of the TxY motif in ERK #
###################################################################
# We assume an ordered mechanism of dual phosphorylation (Lee et al., 2019).
# See also Piala et al. (2014) and references therein.
# We assume that phosphorylation is non-processive, i.e., 
# monophosphorylation TEpY is a possible outcome of MEK-ERK interaction.
# The Y residue in the TxY motif must be phosphorylated before the T residue.
# Activation of kinase activity requires phosphorylation of the T in the TxY motif, i.e.,
# phosphorylation of the Y in the TxY motif is a prerequisite for T phosphorylation and does
# significantly upregulate kinase activity.
# We assume proximity-mediated catalysis.
# The kinase activity of MEK1 depends on activating phosphorylation of S218 and S222.
# The kinase activity of MEK2 depends on activating phosphorylation of S222 and S226.
MEK1(D!1,S218~P,S222~P).ERK1(DRS!1,T202~0,Y204~P)->MEK1(D!1,S218~P,S222~P).ERK1(DRS!1,T202~P,Y204~P) keff_MEK1_ERK1_T202
MEK1(D!1,S218~P,S222~P).ERK1(DRS!1,Y204~0)->MEK1(D!1,S218~P,S222~P).ERK1(DRS!1,Y204~P) keff_MEK1_ERK1_Y204
MEK2(D!1,S222~P,S226~P).ERK1(DRS!1,T202~0,Y204~P)->MEK2(D!1,S222~P,S226~P).ERK1(DRS!1,T202~P,Y204~P) keff_MEK2_ERK1_T202
MEK2(D!1,S222~P,S226~P).ERK1(DRS!1,Y204~0)->MEK2(D!1,S222~P,S226~P).ERK1(DRS!1,Y204~P) keff_MEK2_ERK1_Y204
MEK1(D!1,S218~P,S222~P).ERK2(DRS!1,T185~0,Y187~P)->MEK1(D!1,S218~P,S222~P).ERK2(DRS!1,T185~P,Y187~P) keff_MEK1_ERK2_T185
MEK1(D!1,S218~P,S222~P).ERK2(DRS!1,Y187~0)->MEK1(D!1,S218~P,S222~P).ERK2(DRS!1,Y187~P) keff_MEK1_ERK2_Y187
MEK2(D!1,S222~P,S226~P).ERK2(DRS!1,T185~0,Y187~P)->MEK2(D!1,S222~P,S226~P).ERK2(DRS!1,T185~P,Y187~P) keff_MEK2_ERK2_T185
MEK2(D!1,S222~P,S226~P).ERK2(DRS!1,Y187~0)->MEK2(D!1,S222~P,S226~P).ERK2(DRS!1,Y187~P) keff_MEK2_ERK2_Y187
########################################################################### 
# ERK-mediated phosphorylation of T292 in the proline-rich region of MEK1 #
###########################################################################
# We assume a distributive (vs. processive) mechanism.
# We assume proximity-mediated catalysis.
# The kinase activity of ERK1 depends on activating phosphorylation of T202 and Y204.
# The kinase activity of ERK2 depends on activating phosphorylation of T185 and Y187.
ERK1(DRS!1).MEK1(D!1,T292~0)->ERK1(DRS!1).MEK1(D!1,T292~P) keff_ERK1_MEK1_T292
ERK2(DRS!1).MEK1(D!1,T292~0)->ERK2(DRS!1).MEK1(D!1,T292~P) keff_ERK2_MEK1_T292
########################### 
# ERK1/2 homodimerization #
###########################
# Has the ERK dimer been structurally characterized? <<---- Q8
# No ERK1/ERK2 heterodimers? <<---- Q9
##########################################################
# reversible recruitment of phosphatase to pT292 in MEK1 #
##########################################################
# Which phosphatase mediates negative feedback dephosphorylation? <<---- Q10

####################################################################################
# ERK-regulated pT292-dependent negative feedback dephosphorylation of phospho-MEK #
####################################################################################

##################################################
# constitutive dephosphorylation of phosphosites #
##################################################
# We assume that all phosphosites are dephosphorylated via an unregulated pseudo first-order process.
MEK1(S218~P)->MEK1(S218~0) kpase
MEK1(S222~P)->MEK1(S222~0) kpase
MEK1(T292~P)->MEK1(T292~0) kpase
MEK2(S222~P)->MEK2(S222~0) kpase
MEK2(S226~P)->MEK2(S226~0) kpase
ERK1(T202~P)->ERK1(T202~0) kpase
ERK1(Y204~P)->ERK1(Y204~0) kpase
ERK2(T185~P)->ERK2(T185~0) kpase
ERK2(Y187~P)->ERK2(Y187~0) kpase
end reaction rules
end model
begin actions
generate_network({overwrite=>1})
# equilibration simulation
simulate({suffix=>"equil",method=>"ode",t_end=>180,n_steps=>180,print_functions=>1})
# production simulation
end actions